04139nam a22005655i 9780674985902DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20182018mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806749859027 a10.4159/97806749859022doi  a(DE-B1597)501490  a(OCoLC)1055763919  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aBR525b.C86 2018eb 7aREL1080202bisacsh04a361.7/509732231 aCurtis, Heather D., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHoly Humanitarians :bAmerican Evangelicals and Global Aid /cHeather D. Curtis. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2018  a1 online resource (344 p.) :b24 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOn May 10, 1900, an enthusiastic Brooklyn crowd bid farewell to the Quito. The ship sailed for famine-stricken Bombay, carrying both tangible relief-thousands of tons of corn and seeds-and "a tender message of love and sympathy from God's children on this side of the globe to those on the other." The Quito may never have gotten under way without support from the era's most influential religious newspaper, the Christian Herald, which urged its American readers to alleviate poverty and suffering abroad and at home. In Holy Humanitarians, Heather D. Curtis argues that evangelical media campaigns transformed how Americans responded to domestic crises and foreign disasters during a pivotal period for the nation. Through graphic reporting and the emerging medium of photography, evangelical publishers fostered a tremendously popular movement of faith-based aid that rivaled the achievements of competing agencies like the American Red Cross. By maintaining that the United States was divinely ordained to help the world's oppressed and needy, the Christian Herald linked humanitarian assistance with American nationalism at a time when the country was stepping onto the global stage. Social reform, missionary activity, disaster relief, and economic and military expansion could all be understood as integral features of Christian charity. Drawing on rigorous archival research, Curtis lays bare the theological motivations, social forces, cultural assumptions, business calculations, and political dynamics that shaped America's ambivalent embrace of evangelical philanthropy. In the process she uncovers the seeds of today's heated debates over the politics of poverty relief and international aid.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aChristian Herald (Firm). 0aChristian herald. 0aChristianity in mass mediaxHistoryy20th century. 0aChristianity in mass media-History-20th century. 0aEvangelicalismzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aEvangelicalism-United States-History-20th century. 0aHumanitarian assistance, AmericanxHistoryy20th century. 0aHumanitarian assistance, American-History-20th century. 7aRELIGION / Christian Church / History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060662140uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674985902?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674985902423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674985902/original  a978-3-11-060662-1  Harvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles